🚀 Project Overview
In an era where cyber threats evolve faster than manual defenses—zero-day exploits, APTs, polymorphic malware, and AI-driven attacks—traditional rule-based and signature-based firewalls are obsolete. This project develops an Adaptive Firewall using Reinforcement Learning (RL), enabling the system to autonomously learn optimal traffic filtering policies in real time through trial-and-error interaction with network environments.
The RL agent treats network traffic as an environment:

State: Normalized flow features (packet size, duration, protocols, etc.)
Actions: Allow, Drop, Quarantine (isolate + log), Alert
Rewards: Heavy penalties for false positives, bonuses for blocking threats

By leveraging algorithms like Deep Q-Network (DQN) and Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO), the firewall transcends static rules and supervised ML limitations, adapting to unseen attacks without human intervention.
Goal: Achieve ≥95% accuracy on known threats, ≥85% on zero-days, and ≤2% false positives—paving the way for truly proactive, self-defending networks.
🎯 Key Features & Innovations

Custom OpenAI Gym-compatible environment for realistic simulation
Flow-level analysis using datasets: CIC-IDS2018, UNSW-NB15, IoT-23
Robust reward shaping for low false positives and fast convergence
Adversarial robustness testing (FGSM, PGD attacks)
Real-time dashboard (Streamlit/Flask) for visualization
Reproducible with PyTorch 2.4.0 + Stable-Baselines3 1.8.0

